  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Mobile UI Space**\n\nI\'m currently focused on the mobile UI. I\'ve noted that `FarLeftSpine` and `RightSpine` components consume 112px of valuable screen width. I need to consider options to minimize this, perhaps through collapsing or alternative layouts to reclaim this real estate.\n\n\n**Refining Mobile Layout Strategy**\n\nI\'ve been drilling down on optimizing the mobile layout. I\'ve realized that the current padding on the Left Hemisphere further reduces usable space. My new strategy is to hide both `FarLeftSpine` and `RightSpine` on smaller screens. This involves deciding how users will access key functionalities like the \"Central de Projetos\" on mobile, with a header/drawer or a compact floating access button being considered.\n\n\n**Exploring Mobile Header Options**\n\nI\'m now investigating `App.tsx`\'s header, specifically for mobile. \"Iniciar Jornada\" already exists. I see \"Est\303\272dio\" is hidden on mobile, which is a key focus. To solve this, I\'m considering a minimalist menu button linked to a mobile drawer, or direct `ProjectHub` access. A fixed bottom action bar on mobile also offers an elegant solution and is highly preferable. I\'m leaning toward a luxurious, persistent bottom bar for mobile to ensure a great UX. This mobile bottom bar design will include \"Projetos\" to kick off the ProjectHub.\n\n\n**Optimizing Content Presentation**\n\nI\'m now focused on content readability across devices. I\'m experimenting with adjustments to padding and layout in `/src/App.tsx` and related components, specifically for mobile. I aim to improve full-width text presentation by refining padding classes. I\'m exploring hiding the `FarLeftSpine` and `RightSpine` components on smaller screens to maximize content space. I\'ve noted that `px-4 md:px-8 md:pl-24 lg:pr-8` yields excellent results.\n\n\n**Designing Mobile Utility Bar**\n\nI\'m now designing an extremely elegant action system for mobile. I plan to use a high-end sticky bottom utility bar when `FarLeftSpine` and `RightSpine` are hidden. This premium design includes a clean logo and menu trigger in the header, and a flat, glassy bottom container with icons and labels like \"Projetos\", \"Conversar\", and \"Instagram\". I\'m also ensuring the layout is uncluttered with fluid spacing and typography, and I am focused on touch-friendly 3D Model interactions.\n\n\n**Implementing Mobile Component Hiding**\n\nI\'ve successfully hidden `FarLeftSpine` and `RightSpine` on smaller screens. I modified their styles to include `hidden md:flex`, ensuring they only appear on medium-sized screens and up. I\'m satisfied with the immediate improvement in content space. Now I need to design the mobile header/utility bar, and test the `handleCanvasClick` responsiveness on various devices.\n\n\n**Refining Mobile Header Layout**\n\nI\'m now refining the mobile header. I\'ve adjusted the padding to `px-4 md:px-8 py-4 md:py-6`, making it responsive across devices. I\'m focusing on the \"Jo\303\243o Brito\302\256\" logo and the \"Iniciar Jornada\" button, which could wrap on smaller screens. My design focus is on a premium feel, considering a slide-out main navbar or a glassy floating navigation deck for mobile.\n\n\n**Designing Mobile Bottom Navigation**\n\nI\'m now designing the mobile bottom navigation bar, which will be a glassy, floating element at the bottom center. This modern approach, inside a sticky tray, is ideal for thumb-friendly interaction and keeps the screen clean. I\'m prioritizing easy reach and a premium feel.\n\n\n**Evaluating Mobile Button Placement**\n\nI\'m now evaluating a new button arrangement for mobile. I\'ve designed a clean bottom navigation bar with \"Portf\303\263lio\" and \"Conversar\" buttons. These will open modals. I\'m focusing on ensuring they are highly functional. I\'ll analyze how `App.tsx`\'s grid and padding are currently configured.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 13
      nanos: 619063694
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
