  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing the Instructions**\n\nOkay, I\'m diving into the specifics. I\'m taking the initial request apart piece by piece: keyframing the video to trigger on scroll, integrating it into the hero section, and understanding the user\'s intent. The user also gave a reference to Jo\303\243o. I understand it is a specific video. Now I am dissecting each directive to ensure a comprehensive solution.\n\n\n**Implementing Scroll-Scrubbing**\n\nI\'m now focused on the technical implementation of scroll-scrubbing. My goal is to elegantly link the scroll position to the video\'s `.currentTime`. I am considering how to determine the scroll percentage, whether it\'s globally or within the hero section, the latter seemingly more logical given the context. I\'m visualizing a premium, styled container for the video within the Hero section, a beautifully framed element which highlights the video (Jo\303\243o).\n\n\n**Refining Scroll Calculation**\n\nI\'m now refining the scroll percentage calculation to optimize video scrubbing. To avoid choppy playback, I\'m focusing on efficient event listening and progress calculation. I\'m considering both global page scroll and Hero section-specific scroll as potential drivers for `.currentTime` updates. Based on the user\'s intent to integrate the video within the hero section, the latter appears more relevant. I\'m also planning to maintain video advancement beyond the Hero section.\n\n\n**Calculating Video Duration**\n\nI\'m now focusing on calculating the video\'s duration to link scroll progress to `.currentTime`. The approach involves either reading video metadata upon loading or directly referencing the video\'s full length. My plan is to set `video.currentTime` dynamically as `duration * progress`, which auto-adapts to different video lengths. I\'ve also been exploring how to calculate the scroll progress.\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI\'m checking how to get scroll progress; I\'ve thought through tracking global scroll. Using React, I\'m defining `useState` hooks to track both scroll progress and video progress, using an event listener, or animation frames, I can smoothly interpolate the video\'s target time. I am planning a React hook to handle scroll events for the video\'s `.currentTime`. I am working on a `useEffect` to listen to scroll events and calculate progress.\n\n\n**Implementing React Hook**\n\nI\'m now implementing the React hook to manage scroll events and video time updates. I\'ve integrated `useEffect` to manage event listeners for scroll, and am working on ensuring smooth interpolation of the video time. I\'ve added a ref to the video element to access the `.currentTime` property. I\'ve also incorporated logic to handle video metadata loading to determine the video duration correctly. I\'m exploring linear interpolation (lerp) for a smoother scroll effect.\n\n\n**Refining Interpolation for Scrubbing**\n\nI\'ve realized that to make the scroll-scrubbing look incredibly professional and high-end, smooth interpolation is key. I\'m using a `requestAnimationFrame` loop, and employing a lerp approach to achieve buttery-smooth scrubbing. The code implements smooth interpolation with a `lerp` factor for an elegant experience. I\'m currently working to integrate the code to the React hook.\n\n\n**Optimizing Time Interpolation**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `requestAnimationFrame` loop to smooth out video scrubbing. I\'m applying linear interpolation for seamless time updates, removing any stuttering and creating a premium user experience. I\'ve set the lerp factor to 0.1, making the scrubbing feel amazing. I\'ve added a clamp to `currentTime`, as well.\n\n\n**Testing Video Implementation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on ensuring consistent and reliable video scrubbing across browsers, particularly on mobile. Implementing `preload=\"auto\"`, `muted`, and `playsInline` seems critical. The key is to pause the video initially and then use `video.currentTime` to control scrubbing. I\'m visualizing using a video tag in the hero section, within the `/src/App.tsx` file. Now I\'m mentally testing this approach. It looks good!\n\n\n**Integrating the Copy**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided copy into the hero section, focusing on its visual presentation and animation. I\'m focusing on the `animate-fade-rise` animations, ensuring the text content smoothly reveals itself as the user engages. I\'ve focused on aligning this copy to Jo\303\243o\'s video and ensuring this looks excellent. I will now integrate this on the `/src/App.tsx` file.\n\n\n**Positioning the Video**\n\nI\'m now integrating the video directly within the hero section\'s layout. I\'m focusing on positioning the video element inside of the grid layout: specifically in the `col-span-12 lg:col-span-7` column. I am planning on keeping it very visual; it should look premium. I\'m planning to make the video a visual anchor.\n\n\n**Designing the Video Display**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in designing a premium display for Jo\303\243o\'s video within the hero section. I\'ve realized the initial faint global background is unnecessary; the video should be a striking local element. I\'m focusing on crafting a luxury display card for the video, envisioning a beautifully structured dual layout or an elegant grid element. I\'m prioritizing the video\'s placement, specifically within the `col-span-12 lg:col-span-7` column, to create a premium editorial aesthetic with a sleek video frame as a visual anchor. I\'m starting by designing a container with `relative overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-stone-`.\n\n\n**Designing the UI**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in designing a premium UI for Jo\303\243o\'s video within the hero section. I\'ve designed a luxury display card for the video, incorporating a custom frame with a \"ROLO ATIVO &mdash; SCRUB AO DESLIZAR\" tag. I\'m also implementing a horizontal scroll-progress bar overlay, and a description badge, to enhance the user experience. I\'m currently creating the display as a visually appealing grid element. Now, let me check the imports and existing code in `/src/App.tsx`.\n\n\n**Refactoring Video Integration**\n\nI\'m now refactoring the existing background video layer in `/src/App.tsx`. I\'m replacing it with the scroll-scrubbing video element within the hero section, keeping its source and the styling, and implementing a full integration as a premium visual anchor. I\'m focusing on ensuring it scrubs smoothly and responds well to scroll events. I\'m adding `useRef` to handle the video element.\n\n\n**Refining UI Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating the updated UI elements: custom frame, scroll-progress bar, and description badge. I\'m focusing on ensuring they\'re responsive and visually consistent within the hero section. I\'m aiming for a clean, intuitive layout that enhances the video content and scroll-scrubbing experience. I am now working on the responsive integration of UI components on the `/src/App.tsx` file.\n\n\n**Confirming Paused Video**\n\nI\'ve determined the video must start paused, as manual scrubbing controls playback. I updated the React hook to ensure the video initially remains paused. This way, `.currentTime` manages video progression rather than autoplay.\n\n\n"
